🔷 First: How memory worked in normal (platform) threads

👉 Every platform thread (OS thread) has:

-A fixed stack size (usually ~1 MB)
-Allocated upfront

❌ Problem:

Even if your method uses very little memory:

void simple() {
    int x = 10;
}

👉 Still gets ~1 MB stack reserved 😐

👉 If you create 10,000 threads:

💥 ~10 GB memory needed → not scalable


🔷 Now: How Virtual Threads handle memory

Virtual threads do NOT use a fixed OS stack

Instead, they use:

👉 Stack stored in heap (as small chunks)

🔷 1️⃣ Stack grows/shrinks dynamically

✅ How it works:

a.Virtual thread stack is not allocated fully
b.It starts very small
c.Grows only when needed

🧠 Example:
void a() { b(); }
void b() { c(); }
void c() { }

👉 Stack frames created only for:

a → b → c

👉 If deeper calls → stack grows
👉 If methods return → stack shrinks

🔥 Key difference:

(i)Thread Type	Stack
(ii)Platform thread	Fixed (1 MB)
(iii)Virtual thread	Dynamic (few KB → grows)


🔷 2️⃣ Stack is stored in Heap (not OS memory)

👉 Virtual thread stack is broken into small segments (stack chunks)

(i)  Stored in JVM heap
(ii) Managed like normal objects


✅ Why this helps:

JVM can:

(i)Allocate small memory pieces
(ii)Free unused parts quickly
(iii)Reuse memory

🧠 Analogy:

Platform thread:

Book 1000-page notebook even if you write 2 pages

Virtual thread:

Use small notebooks, add pages only when needed

🔷 3️⃣ Stack is released when thread is paused (VERY IMPORTANT)

When virtual thread hits blocking call:

Thread.sleep(1000);

👉 JVM does:

(i)Saves stack into heap
(ii)Releases OS thread
(iii)Stack memory can be optimized/reused

✅ Improvement in Java 25:

(i)Faster serialization/deserialization of stack
(ii)Less memory retained during pause
(iii)Better reuse of freed stack chunks


🔷 4️⃣ Better Memory Reuse

👉 JVM maintains pool of stack chunks

Instead of:

Creating new memory every time ❌

It:

Reuses old chunks ✅
🧠 Example:

Thread 1 finishes → memory freed
Thread 2 starts → uses same memory

👉 Less allocation → less GC → better performance

🔷 5️⃣ Less GC Pressure

Earlier:

Many temporary objects → more garbage collection

Now:

(i)Reused stack chunks
(ii)Fewer allocations

👉 GC runs less frequently

